Subtask 4.3: Verify Evidence Integrity
# Final integrity check
cd ~/forensics_lab

echo "Performing final evidence integrity verification..."

# Recalculate hashes
md5sum evidence_usb.img > final_check.md5
sha256sum evidence_usb.img > final_check.sha256

# Compare with original hashes
echo "Comparing hash values:"
diff evidence_usb.img.md5 final_check.md5
diff evidence_usb.img.sha256 final_check.sha256

if [ $? -eq 0 ]; then
    echo "SUCCESS: Evidence integrity maintained throughout analysis"
else
    echo "WARNING: Hash mismatch detected - investigate immediately"
fi

# Clean up temporary files
rm final_check.md5 final_check.sha256
Troubleshooting Common Issues
Issue 1: Autopsy Won't Start
# Check if port 9999 is already in use
netstat -tlnp | grep 9999

# Kill existing Autopsy processes
pkill -f autopsy

# Restart Autopsy
cd ~/forensics_lab
autopsy &
Issue 2: Cannot Mount Loop Device
# Check available loop devices
losetup -a

# Find free loop device
sudo losetup -f

# Use the free device (replace X with available number)
sudo losetup /dev/loopX evidence_usb.img
Issue 3: Browser Cannot Connect
# Check if Autopsy is running
ps aux | grep autopsy

# Check firewall settings
sudo ufw status

# Verify localhost connectivity
curl -I http://localhost:9999/autopsy
Key Concepts Summary
Digital Forensics: The process of collecting, preserving, analyzing, and presenting digital evidence in a legally admissible manner.

Chain of Custody: Documentation that tracks the handling of evidence from collection to presentation, ensuring integrity and admissibility.

Hash Values: Cryptographic checksums used to verify evidence integrity and detect any modifications.

File System Artifacts: Digital traces left by file system operations, including metadata, deleted files, and timeline information.

Timeline Analysis: Chronological examination of file system events to reconstruct user activity and system changes.

